so, we'd be compelled to get more positive as we do see positive asymmetry here. Post- earnings our estimates don't change materially, though our PT bumps up to \(\) 117\(as our FY27 EPS creeps up to\) \ \(8.98\) . Remain EW for now.

\((\equiv)\) Public sector a notable headwind that masked a decent quarter otherwise. US public sector revenue declined \(26\%\) Y/Y in the July quarter, primarily due to delays in deploying budgets to various government agencies. Excluding this segment (which was \(8\%\) of revenue), the rest of the business grew \(5\%\) Y/Y in the July quarter (vs. just \(+1\%\) Y/Y for total revenue), led by strength in Americas large enterprises and mid- market customers, partially offset by pockets of weakness in EMEA and APAC. Looking forward, we expect US public customers to remain a drag on NTAP's revenue growth, but would expect the double- digit Y/Y declines from this cohort to improve given management's expectations for LSD- MSD Y/Y total company revenue growth in F2H. Nevertheless, this remains a risk we need to continue tracking.

\((\pm)\) Are we seeing clearer evidence of enterprises modernizing their on- prem storage? Over the past few years, the majority of the data center spending has been on AI training, limiting the pace of modernization for on- prem storage arrays. However, it seems this is starting to change. As more and more workloads transition from training to inferencing, there should be a growing need to upgrade to higher performant storage, and NTAP mgmt highlighted that they closed 125 AI infrastructure and data lake modernization deals in the quarter, a more than \(100\%\) Y/Y increase vs. 50 of these deals signed in the year ago quarter. This is an encouraging sign as it's been multiple quarters where our checks anecdotally highlight this modernization opportunity in the storage market without it actually materializing in storage vendor results. And even though the dollar value of NTAP's AI deals signed this quarter don't necessarily appear robust, it's encouraging to see progress as we see the potential for lower interest rates and OBBBA benefits to support more robust storage modernization efforts in 2026.

\((\pm)\) A modest public cloud miss, but momentum remains. Public Cloud revenue in FIQ came in \(5\%\) below our and Consensus estimates. However, under the hood, we don't believe the results were as negative as the \(1\%\) Y/Y as reported growth, as when normalizing for the Spot divestiture Public Cloud grew \(18\%\) Y/Y. Looking forward, we believe this business can sustain double digit organic revenue growth through FY26, and importantly, the parts of this business that are growing the fastest are higher margin, resulting in mgmt increasing their gross margin guide for Public Cloud to \(80 - 85\%\) , from \(75 - 80\%\) .
